# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The **21st G7 summit** was held on June 15–17, 1995 in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The venue for this summit meeting was Summit Place in Halifax.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] It was labelled by Prime Minister Jean Chrétien as a "Chevrolet Summit", using a utilitarian automobile as a metaphor for the summit being less expensive than previous summits in Versailles and Venice.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The Group of Seven (G7) is an unofficial forum which brought together the heads of the richest industrialized countries: France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada (since 1976), and the President of the European Commission (starting officially in 1981).
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The G7 is an unofficial annual forum for the leaders of Canada, the European Commission, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] Boris Yeltsin was also in attendance representing Russia.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The 21st G7 summit was the first summit for French President Jacques Chirac and the last summit for Japanese Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] It was also the first and only summit for Italian Prime Minister Lamberto Dini.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] The summit was intended as a venue for resolving differences among its members.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] As a practical matter, the summit was also conceived as an opportunity for its members to give each other mutual encouragement in the face of difficult economic decisions.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] This was the first year that the G8 summit was marked by an official World Wide Web site on the Internet sponsored by the Canadian Government.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/21st-g7-summit] Two unofficial web pages were also created, one set up by Dalhousie University in Halifax, the summit site, and the other created by teachers and students of Cornwallis Junior High School there.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] The shipyard was founded in 1947 on the site of the World War II Norwegian military training facility Camp Norway.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] Today it manufactures welded marine-grade aluminum boats, ranging from 16 feet (5 m) up to 65 feet (20 m) in length, to both custom-made and standardized designs.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] Its 26,000 square feet (2,415 m2) facility includes 3D modeling capabilities.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] In February 2011, ABCO Industries Ltd won the bid to build two 56 feet (17 m)-long aluminum vessels, operating at a service speed of 18 knots, for Halifax and Saint John.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] The contract was signed between ABCO Industries and the Atlantic Pilotage Authority, with vessels built according to the designs of naval architect Rory MacDonald of Lengkeek Vessel Engineering.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] ABCO is building 12 metres (39 ft) landing craft for Harry DeWolf-class offshore patrol vessels.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] To date, the shipyard has made four vessels for Fisheries and Oceans Canada (DFO), including the scientific research vessel CCGS Kelso.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/abco-industries] As part of the Government of Canada's commitment to upgrading the Canadian Coast Guard fleet, the shipyard is contracted to build another a 46 feet (14 m)-long inshore patrol vessel to be based at Prince Edward Island.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] He was born in Beach Meadow, Queens County, Nova Scotia, to Martin Pentz and Eliza Jane Maxwell.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] From a young age, Pentz had always taken a strong interest in ships.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] As he became older, his passion for ships turned into his livelihood.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] The combination of his talent for woodwork, and knowledge of ships, created a foundation for a lifetime of success in his field of work.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] He began his career in 1872 as an itinerant ship builder.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] He slowed his career down briefly around 1891 when he married Annie Matthews (on October 24, 1891).
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] Pentz and his family eventually moved on to Shelburne to continue his work with shipbuilding.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] He was employed at the Joseph McGill Ship Yard, where he set a new example for what skills a master ship builder should have.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] Over is lifetime he produced an impressive one hundred and forty-one ships.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] In 1901 the *Harbinger* was built, and in 1902 the *Messenger* was completed, both of these ships were steam trawlers, and were the first steam powered fishing vessels build at these docks.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] The *Arbutus*, built in 1903, was the first auxiliary powered fishing schooner built in the province of Nova Scotia.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] These two ships were renowned for their remarkable speed and celebrated by authors such as Frederick William Wallace.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] Both latter vessels competed for the Britain Cup in Nova Scotia's fisherman's regatta, which was held in Digby, Nova Scotia in 1911.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/amos-pentz] Not only was he a fine ship builder, but he also was an inspiring mentor to James Havelock Harding who grew to become another one of Shelburne's best ship builders, he eventually moved to the United States to continue his career.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The Atlantic Provinces are the historical territories of the Mi'kmaq, Wolastoqiyik, Naskapi, Beothuk and Nunatsiavut peoples.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The people of Nunatsiavut are the Labrador Inuit (Labradormiut), who are descended from the Thule people.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Leif Erikson and other members of his family began exploring the North American coast in 986 CE.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Leif landed in three places, and in the third established a small settlement called Vinland.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The location of Vinland is uncertain, but an archaeological site on the northern tip of Newfoundland at L'Anse aux Meadows has been identified as a good candidate.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] It was a modest Viking settlement and is the oldest confirmed presence of Europeans in North America.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The Vikings would make brief excursions to North America for the next 200 years, though further attempts at colonization were thwarted.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The site produced the first evidence of pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact of Europeans with the Americas outside of Greenland.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Acadia, a colony of New France, was established in areas of present-day Atlantic Canada in 1604, under the leadership of Samuel de Champlain and Pierre Dugua, Sieur de Mons.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The French would form alliances with many indigenous groups within Atlantic Canada, including the Mi'kmaq of Acadia, who joined the Wabanaki Confederacy, important allies to New France.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Competition for control of the island of Newfoundland and its waters contributed to major ongoing conflicts and occasional wars between France and Britain.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Despite reoccurring wars and conflicts, Britain acquiesced to France's demands for continuing access to this fishery.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Between 1755 and 1764 during the Seven Years' War the British forcibly removed thousands of Acadians from Nova Scotia and New Brunswick in an event known as the Great Expulsion or Le Grand Dérangement.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] After the signing of the Treaty of Paris in 1764 some of the Acadians returned and settled in the area that would become New Brunswick.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The effect of this migration can still be seen today as the province of New Brunswick is the only officially bilingual province in Canada with over a quarter of residents speaking French at home.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] After the conclusion of the American Revolution with the signing of the Treaty of Paris in 1783 many loyalists from the United States settled in the region.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] This influx of immigrants caused the partition of Nova Scotia creating New Brunswick.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Additionally these immigrants changed the culture and character of the region which had historically been French towards more British styled communities.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] It also marked one of the first large waves of migration to the area that established a predominantly Anglo-Canadian population.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Some of the new settlers brought with them Black slaves.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Also 3,000 Black loyalists who were slaves during the war and who sided with the British were given freedom and evacuated with other Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Most of the free Blacks settled at Birchtown, the most prominent Black township in North America at the time.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The War of 1812 significantly impacted the provinces of Atlantic Canada where they played crucial roles in naval operations, privateering, and as strategic support bases for the British war effort against the United States.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] In the last half of the 19th century the region's population grew due to the immigration from Ireland due to the great potato famine.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Saint John and Halifax, both port cities, particularly received a significant influx of Irish immigrants within the region, with Saint John's quarantine station on Partridge Island being the second-busiest in British North America during the epidemic typhus outbreak.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The first premier of Newfoundland, Joey Smallwood, coined the term "Atlantic Canada" when the Dominion of Newfoundland joined Canada in 1949.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] He believed that it would have been presumptuous for Newfoundland to assume that it could include itself within the existing term "Maritime provinces," which was used to describe the cultural similarities shared by New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island, and Nova Scotia.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The other provinces of Atlantic Canada entered Confederation during the 19th century with New Brunswick and Nova Scotia being founding members of the Dominion of Canada in 1867, and later Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Atlantic Canada is characterized by its rugged coastlines, gravel beaches, rugged mountains, and dense forests.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The area is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the east and south and Quebec to the west.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The region shares two international borders one with the United States and its State of Maine and another off the coast of Newfoundland with France and its overseas collectivity of Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The region's maritime environment has influenced the region's climate, culture, and economy.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The area encompasses a mix of urban centers like Halifax and St.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] John's and rural communities that rely on fishing, and tourism.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Although Quebec has a physical Atlantic coast on the Gulf of St.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Lawrence, it is generally not considered an Atlantic Province; instead, it is classified as part of Central Canada, along with Ontario.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Atlantic and Central Canada together are also known as Eastern Canada.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Atlantic Canada includes a section of the Appalachian Mountains known as the Appalachian Uplands.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] In each Atlantic province, Upland regions have been divided into three highland areas.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The mountain range results in coastal regions being fjorded.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Some areas contain glaciofluvial deposits.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Atlantic Canada's primary industries are natural resource extraction and power generation including fishing, hydroelectricity, wind power, forestry, oil, and mining.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The Atlantic provinces contribute a large part of Canada's fish production, with many coastal communities primarily dependent on fisheries.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Over half of all ocean related jobs in Canada are found in Atlantic Canada with 75% of the ocean economy centered in its provinces.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The access point for many of such fisheries being the Gulf of St.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Lawrence and the Atlantic continental shelf.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Due to the collapse of the Atlantic northwest cod fishery Canada imposed a moratorium of cod fishing in 1992.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] This affected the region significantly and caused the loss of between 30,000 and 50,000 jobs in the region which was the largest single layoff in Canadian history.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The Atlantic Canada Opportunities Agency is the official agency responsible for creating economic opportunities within Atlantic Canada.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Labrador hosts the second largest hydroelectric system in Canada at Churchill Falls where it produces 35,000 GWh of power each year.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Elsewhere in the region wind power and hydrogen generation have begun to make a large impact on the energy landscape including exporting energy to Canada and hydrogen overseas.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] The region is host to parts of Canada's eastern boreal forests which were historically used for timber production and boat production.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] Nova Scotia has historically been an exporter of gypsum and now produces over 60% of the gypsum in Canada.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-canada] In the Atlantic provinces, iron, anhydrite, salt, coal, limestone, silica, sand, quartz, marble, slate, sandstone, granite, and peat are also mined.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-oak] In 2008 the dredging barge *Shovel Master* capsized after experiencing rough seas while being towed by *Atlantic Larch* from Saint John to Halifax for a refit.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-oak] The crew were rescued by a CH-149 Cormorant search and rescue helicopter shortly before the barge capsized near Yarmouth.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-oak] *Atlantic Oak* towed the capsized, but still floating barge, for only 150m before it sank, spilling thousands of gallons of diesel fuel, hydraulic fluid and waste oil.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-oak] On Jan 15th, 2013 the boat was seen guiding the damaged HMCS *Athabaskan* into dock at the NC jetty in Halifax.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-spruce-tug] Atlantic Towing's *Atlantic Spruce* was on her way to Vera Cruz, Mexico, on September 24–26, 1997.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-spruce-tug] She was previously stationed at Statia Terminals in Port Hawkesbury.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/atlantic-spruce-tug] She was the second Atlantic tug to go to Mexico.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The **Maritime Museum of the Atlantic** is a maritime museum located in downtown Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum is a member institution of the Nova Scotia Museum and is the oldest and largest maritime museum in Canada with a collection of over 30,000 artifacts including 70 small craft and a steamship: the CSS *Acadia*, a 180-foot steam-powered hydrographic survey ship launched in 1913.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] It was first known as the Maritime Museum of Canada and located at HMC Dockyard, the naval base on Halifax Harbour.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Several naval officers served as volunteer chairs of the museum until 1959 when Niels Jannasch was hired as the museum's founding director, serving until 1985.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum moved through several locations over the next three decades before its current building was constructed in 1981 as part of a waterfront redevelopment program.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum received the CSS *Acadia* in 1982.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Today the museum is part of the Nova Scotia Museum system.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum was one of the first attractions to open on the redeveloped Halifax Waterfront.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Its location provides the museum with several piers and boatsheds, as well as a strategic view of the Halifax Harbour, which looks seaward towards the Harbourmaster office and Georges Island and across to Dartmouth.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Among its facilities is the restored 1880s Robertson Store ship chandler building, as well as modern exhibit galleries in the Devonian Wing (the modern museum building).
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] HMCS *Sackville*, a World War II Flower-class corvette is docked adjacent to the museum in the summer months but is not owned or administered by the museum.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Also, the flags across the front of the building read, "Welcome aboard L44 38N G63 34W"--giving it's **L**atitude and lon**G**itude in degrees and minutes.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] In addition to the over 30,000 artifacts, the museum also has a collection of 30,000 photographs as well as a large collection of charts and rare books.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] A reference library, open to the public, is named after the museum's founding director, The Niels Jannasch Library.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum has Canada's largest collection of ship portraits including the oldest ship portrait in Canada as well as a large collection of ship models including the original production models of the television show *Theodore Tugboat*.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Ongoing restoration of *Whim*, a 1937 C-class sloop can be found in one of the boatsheds on the wharf behind the museum.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] In addition to this current restoration project, the boatsheds house some of the museum's small craft collection.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] During the summer months three boats in the working small craft collection can be found moored next to the CSS *Acadia*.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] In July 2017 the museum also completed restoration of the small schooner *Hebridee II*.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Public galleries include the Days of Sail, the Age of Steam, Small Craft, the Canadian Navy, the Halifax Explosion, and Shipwrecks.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] A special permanent exhibit explores the sinking of the RMS *Titanic* with an emphasis on Nova Scotia's connection to recovering the bodies of *Titanic* victims.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum has the world's foremost collection of wooden artifacts from *Titanic*, including one of the few surviving deck chairs.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The *Titanic* exhibit also includes a child's pair of shoes, which helped identify *Titanic*'s "unknown child" as Sidney Leslie Goodwin.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The adjacent exhibit "Shipwreck Treasures of Nova Scotia" explores the many other shipwrecks off the coast of Nova Scotia including archaeological discoveries on naval shipwrecks in Louisbourg Harbour and an unknown 1750s schooner at Lower Prospect, Nova Scotia.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The results of treasure hunting are also featured in a section on Cape Breton treasure wrecks which has displays of weapons, instruments, gold and silver from wrecks such as the 1711 HMS *Feversham*, the 1725 wreck of *Chameau* and the 1761 wreck of the ship *Auguste*.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The Age of Steam gallery includes a special display on Samuel Cunard, the Nova Scotian who founded Cunard.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The restored 1880s Robertson building includes the fully restored Robertson ship chandlerly which features hands on foghorns, ropes and ship fittings.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The Navy gallery includes the "Convoy Exhibit" about the Battle of the Atlantic which includes the Canadian Merchant Navy Book of Remembrance.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Monuments to the Canadian and Norwegian Merchant Navy are located just outside the museum along with a unique children's playground in the shape of a submarine.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum also has a changing exhibits gallery.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] A 2009 exhibit *Ship of Fate: The Tragic Voyage of the St.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] Louis* was the first Canadian exhibit to explore the 1939 voyage of the Jewish refugee ship MS *St.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum became the first museum in North America to present an exhibit about the lives of gay seafarers in 2011 when it presented *Hello Sailor: Gay Life on the Ocean Waves*, adapted from an exhibit developed at the Merseyside Maritime Museum in Liverpool, England.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The 2012 exhibit explores the experiences of the cable ships based in Halifax who recovered most of the victims of the RMS *Titanic* sinking.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The corvette HMCS *Sackville* (K181) is not part of the Maritime Museum of the Atlantic but is located adjacent to the museum in the summer and works with the museum to interpret the Royal Canadian Navy.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum's location on the Halifax waterfront has made the museum the site of several significant public events.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] In addition to being a stop on most Canadian federal election campaigns, the museum hosted meetings from the 1995 G7 Summit, as well a September 11 commemorative event in 2006 attended by Canada's Minister of Foreign Affairs, Peter MacKay and United States Secretary of State, Condoleezza Rice.
[src:maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic/maritime-museum-of-the-atlantic] The museum hosts an annual commemoration of the Battle of the Atlantic on the first Sunday of every May and Canadian Merchant Navy day every September 3.
